[SourceTitle "01 Introduction"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "combat-the-caro-kann-with-3exd5/course/11723, variation/675731"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 {A few words about the starting 
position of the variation. Structurally, we are as though we are playing the Black 
side of the Queen's Gambit Declined Carlsbad structure. However, Black does not have 
his typical, comfortable QGD kind of play here, because: 1) White is a tempo up 2) 
White's pieces are more conveniently placed. Bd3 deprives Black's bishop of the f5 
square, and the knight has not yet moved to f3, making Bg4 impossible. Also, White's 
dark-squared bishop will be the first to occupy the h2-b8 diagonal. Thanks to these 
facts it is White who fights for the advantage despite having the 'Black' pawn 
structure. As we will see, White generally relies on active piece play and his 
chances lay mostly in the center and on the kingside, although he can often cause 
early queenside discomfort for Black with Qb3 (when the black bishop leaves c8). The 
play is largely of strategic/positional character, though in some of the lines 
tactical complications arise. The concept of this repertoire is to give you lines 
that are solid, practical, easy-to learn and at the same time challenging for the 
second player. Apart from the introduction, the book is divided into three main 
chapters, covering the main Black's responses: 5...Qc7, 5....g6 and 5....Nf6, and one 
mini-chapter, covering the fourth most popular move 5....e5. Many lines are 
interconnected, either transposing to each other, or (more often) making use of the 
same strategic ideas. I suggest beginning the study of each chapter with the Main 
Line, where I comment on the early moves and general features of the position, as 
well as provide you with the most important lines to remember. An important final 
remark. In writing this book, I was guided by the rule 'quality over quantity'. Most 
of the positions are of non-forcing character, which means it would be impossible to 
cover all the feasible options on every move. So in the less popular positions, I 
cover only the moves which I believe are critical. Also, I do not cover possible 
Black moves which are obviously positionally, strategically or tactically bad, such 
as, to give one example, 5....e6 (burying the c8 bishop). In my view, to get an 
advantage after such moves, no theoretical knowledge is required - you only need to 
rely on general chess rules and play logically. On the other hand, I put an emphasis 
on the lines that require precision and inventiveness and I give you plenty of new, 
sometimes even counter-intuitive conceptions of how to treat the most challenging 
Black's tries. I hope you will have a great time combating the Caro-Kann Defence with 
3. exd5!} *

