1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 {Black prevents the development 
of White's bishop to f4. This had been considered one way to effortless equality for 
Black until an introduction of a brilliant novelty By GM Bartosz Socko in 2014.} 6. 
Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 $1 {This is the great idea by Polish GM Bartosz Socko. 
Having had privilege to work with him, I was one of the first players to use the move 
and was able to catch German GM Rasmus Svane unawares in 2016.} Bd6 {This natural 
move is not the best, as it allows White to demonstrate the whole idea behind 8. 
Qe1.} 9. f3 Bh5 10. Qh4 $1 {The point!} Bg6 11. Bxg6 fxg6 12. Nf4 $1 {Another 
energetic move, forcing Black to compromise his king's position.} Kf7 13. Nh3 $16 
{White creates a threat of Ng5+. The variation could be contiued. However, White's 
advantage is already without question. Black does not have anything to show in return 
for his spoiled structure and weakened king position.} *

