1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 Nf6 
{Another natural developing move. White should continue with his plan.} 9. f3 Bh5 10. 
Qh4 h6 {The point of Black's idea, preventing both Bg5 and Nf4.} 11. Qh3 {White 
creates the threats of Nf4 and Ng3.} Bd6 {See also the more ambitious 11....e5.} 12. 
Ng3 Bxg3 13. Qxg3 Qxg3 14. hxg3 Bg6 15. Be2 $1 {Of course White needs to preserve the 
bishop pair to assure himself of better long-term chances in the endgame.} O-O 16. 
Kf2 {It is useful to improve the king's position not declaring the other pieces' 
positions yet.} Rfe8 {Black should try to prepare ...e5 before White fully develops.} 
17. Na3 a6 {Otherwise the Nb5 threat would be highly unpleasant.} 18. Rd1 b5 19. Bf4 
$14 {White keeps a definite edge thanks to his bishop pair.} *

