1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 Nf6 
9. f3 Bh5 10. Qh4 h6 11. Qh3 e5 {This ambitious move hasn't been tried yet and leads 
to a very complicated play.} 12. Re1 $1 {Forcing ...Be7, as otherwise Black would 
develop comfortably with ...Bd6.} Be7 13. Qg3 $1 {Another important move, forcing 
Black to castle long.} O-O-O 14. Be3 {The position is of a sharp character, but I 
believe White has at least the better practical chances. The following line is 
indicated by a computer:} Rde8 15. Bf2 Bd6 16. Qxg7 $1 Nd7 17. Bh7 $1 {A remarkable 
concept.} Nd8 18. Bf5 e4 19. Ng3 Bg6 20. Qf6 Be7 21. Qe5 Qxe5 22. dxe5 exf3 23. gxf3 
$14 {The smoke has cleared and White preserves a slight edge. Of course there were 
alternatives along the way and the line demands practical testing.} *

[Event "Combat the Caro-Kann with 3.exd5"]
[Site "5....Qc7"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8....Nf6, 10....Rg8"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 5....Qc7"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "combat-the-caro-kann-with-3exd5/course/11723, variation/723597"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 Nf6 
{Another natural developing move. White should continue with his plan.} 9. f3 Bh5 10. 
Qh4 Rg8 $1 {This move, chosen by a Caro-Kann expert Alexey Dreev, hides a venomous 
idea behind itself.} 11. Bxh7 {Apparently, Black has just lost a pawn without 
adequate compensation. But this not the case, as becomes clear after Black's next 
move.} Bxf3 $1 12. Rxf3 Rh8 13. Rxf6 {Forced.} gxf6 {Now we see the point of Black's 
idea. White has two minor pieces for a rook, but his bishop is stuck on h7 without a 
clear way out. I spent a great deal of time analysing this position and while I must 
admit I didn't find a way to an advantage, I believe the line I offer sets Black 
serious practical problems and therefore should be effective.} 14. Bf4 Qb6 15. Nd2 
Ne7 $1 {The only satisfactory move for Black and quite a tough one to find. See also 
the refutaion of the greedy 15....Qxb2.} 16. Nb3 Ng6 17. Qh5 a5 $1 {Another strong 
and non-obvious move. In case of an immediate 17....Bd6 White has a better version of 
the game and can count on an advantage.} 18. Rb1 {White has to defend b2.} Bd6 19. 
Bxd6 Qxd6 {Black now threatens ...Nf8, so White's reply is forced.} 20. Bxg6 $1 Rxh5 
21. Bxh5 $13 {We have reached perhaps the most intriguing position in the repertoire, 
featuring one of the most interesting imbalances in chess: 3 minor pieces vs queen. 
The computer analysis results in a move repetion, but in practice such an outcome 
seems unlikely. White's play lies in the centre and on the kingside. Black's f7-e6-d5 
pawn chain looks solid, but if White amasses his forces around these points, Black 
will have to watch out for potential sacrifices there. The passed h-pawn, while not 
particularly threatening now, remains a long-term asset. Black should, on the other 
hand, try to develop queenside play} ({this is why 17....a5! was more precise than 
the immediate 17....Bd6}) {. He can also try a quick ...e5-e4, anticipating White's 
play in the centre. Note that in order just to reach this position Black had to find 
many non-obvious moves along the way, which should guarantee us at least a 
substantial time advantage.} *

