1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 Nf6 
{Another natural developing move. White should continue with his plan.} 9. f3 Bh5 10. 
Qh4 Rg8 11. Bxh7 Bxf3 12. Rxf3 Rh8 13. Rxf6 gxf6 14. Bf4 Qb6 15. Nd2 Qxb2 $6 {White 
should be happy to see this moves, as in return for the pawns, he gains valuable 
time, which he can use to get the h7-bishop back into play.} 16. Rb1 Qxa2 17. Qh3 $1 
O-O-O 18. Qd3 $1 {Note that Black cannot now trap the bishop with 18....f5 because of 
19. Bxf5!} Qa4 {Preventing 19. Qb5} 19. Bf5 {The tactical point of White's previous 
play.} Bd6 20. Bxd6 Rxd6 21. Qg3 Rdd8 22. Bd3 $14 {White has accomplished his mishop 
of bringing the bishop back into play at the cost of two pawns. Despite material 
equality, his safer king and the misplaced position of black queen give him at least 
slightly better chances.} *

