1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 {This is the most 
popular way to handle the the entire 3.exd5 variation. The move is indeed logical - 
Black needs to develop his light-squared bishop before playing ...e6 and g4 happens 
to be the only available position.} 7. Qb3 {White immediately exploit the lack of 
defence of the b7 point, developing his queen with tempo. Other moves are obviously 
harmless.} Qc8 {The most common response. The queen defends the b7 pawn, without 
exposing itself to a potential attack after a possible Ne5 in the future. The next 
couple of moves from both sides flow naturally.} 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O Bh5 
11. Rae1 Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. h4 $1 {First played by Kramnik versus Ivanchuk in 
World Cup 2017. Then used by Carlsen in chess.com speed chess match verus So in the 
same year. Ironically, both games were lost by the World Champions. However their 
loses had little to do with the opening. I believe that this move, if followed 
accurately offers White promising play.} a6 {The reaction of both Ivanchuk and So 
based on a fine understanding of the position. 13....0-0 would only play into White's 
hands, as after g3, Kg2, Rh1 and Bg5, White threatens Bxf6 and h5, making the rook 
feel useless on f8 compared to h8 and the king less safe on g8 than e8. In my view, 
this is the moment where both Kramnik and Carlsen went astray by playing respectively 
14. c4 and 14. a4. I believe that the old wisdom 'do not play on the wing where you 
are weaker' applies here. Instead, I propose} 14. g3 b5 15. Kg2 $14 {I believe White 
has the better prospects in the upcoming fight. It is a long way until Black's 
queenside play brings him anything substantial. In the meantime, White is ready to 
utilize e5, g5, and in some cases c5 squares with his minor pieces. For example, 
after potential Ng5 and Qc2 threats of sacrifices on e6 and f7 start to appear, 
especcialy if Black queen leaves c8. Should Black decide castle, White switches to an 
already mentioned plan of preapring an opening of the h file.} *

