1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nd2 e6 
9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O {This move, although most often played, is innacurate, as 
Black's bishop will not succeed to get to g6 without being exchanged for the white 
knight.} 11. Ne5 $1 Bh5 12. Qc2 Bd6 {More sensible than 12....Bg6. Black starts to 
activate his pieces.} 13. Rae1 {White's plan generally consists of Bg3 and f4. 
However, it is important to start with 13. Rae1 for the reason outlined below.} Qc7 
14. Bg3 Rac8 15. Qb1 {The point of 13. Rae1. If the rook was on a1, the Nxd4 threat 
would be awkward to meet. Now White smoothly returns his queen to b1, retaining the 
harmony of his pieces.} Rfe8 16. f4 Bg6 {Otherwise 17. Bh4 would follow, with growing 
initiative for White.} 17. Bxg6 {Better than 17. Nxg6, as in this position the knight 
on e5 is clearly more valuable than the d3 bishop.} hxg6 18. Bh4 Ne7 19. Bg5 $1 {Now 
19...Nf5 will be met by 20. g4! Ne7 21. Qd3. White will continue to develop his 
kingside initiative.} *

