1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nd2 e6 
9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qc2 {This move higlights the 
inadvantage of 10....0-0 move order - Black does not have the ...Bg6 resource and is 
instead forced to weaken his kingside.} g6 {This looks more reasonable than 13....h6, 
as it prepares a safe haven on f5 for the bishop. White has not managed to show a way 
to an advantage in this position yet, but I have found a strong improvement.} 14. 
Rfc1 $1 {This is my new move. While it may seem strange, there is perfect logic 
behind it, which will soon demonstrate itself.} Nc5 {The most natural move. See also 
14....Bf5} 15. Nb3 {The point of developing the f1 rook to c1 becomes clear - after 
...Nxb3 axb3, the second rook joins the play via the a file.} Bf5 {It seems 
reasonable for Black to exchange the bishops, as otherwise after Qd2, he may not get 
the second chance.} 16. Bxf5 gxf5 17. c4 $1 {And this is the primary point of 
14.Rfc1. White opens up the game to his advantage.} Rd8 18. Qe2 d4 {Closing the c 
file looks like the lesser evil, but White remains in control.} 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. Rd1 
$16 {With Rd3 and Rad1 coming next, White will exert pressure both at the d4 pawn and 
at the kingside (Rh3-Qh5 ideas).} *

