1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 {The second 
most popular, yet the most natural move. I must say it had been a hard nut to crack 
for me, but I finally found a promising way of playing.} 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. 
Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bd2 {Almost all of the games from this position have continued with 11. 
Bxd6, but in my view after this exchange White cannot hope for any real advantage. 
The move in the game is much more ambitious and promising in the long terrm. White 
preserves his most valuable asset- the bishop pair, and keeps more attacking chances 
on the kingside.} O-O 12. Qc2 {The move order is important, as 12 .0-0 would allow 
...Ne4!} Rac8 13. a3 {Parrying the ...Nb4 threat.} h6 {Otherwise Bg5 would be 
unpleasant for Black- the first effect of keeping the dark-squared bishops on the 
board.} 14. O-O Qc7 15. g3 {Of course White must be consistent and not allow the 
exchange of bishops after ....Bf4} Na5 {Black starts his typical play on the 
queenside.} 16. Rae1 Nc4 17. Qc1 {Creating a threat of Bxh6 and practically forcing 
Black's response.} Nxd2 18. Qxd2 $14 {White has exchanged his dark-squared bishop for 
a knight instead of a bishop. What has he achieved in this way? First of all, the c4 
knight was a key piece in Black's queenside plans. Moreover, we now have an 
opposite-coloured bishop position, which, as we know, naturally favors the attacking 
side. White plans to halt Black's queenside play as long as possible and 
simultaneously prepare an attack on the kingside. Qe2 is a good next move, both 
taking b5 under additional control and preparing Nh4, f4, Nf3-e5, with growing 
initiative on the kingside.} *

