1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 
{One of the oldest lines, pioneered by Capablanca. A most convincing way to counter 
it was shown by Fischer almost half a century ago.} 9. Qc2 e6 10. Nf3 Qb6 {Black 
hurries to exchange his passive light-squared bishop on the b5 square. If he 
succeeds, he will achieve comfortable equality. This explains White's next move.} 11. 
a4 $1 {The key move, first played By Fischer to score a famous victory over Petrosian 
in 1970 USSR vs Rest of the World Match. White stops the bishops exchange and this 
essentially secures his advantage.} Rc8 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. Qb1 Nh5 14. Be3 $16 {White 
is clearly better. See the famous Fischer-Petrosian game.} *

