1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 e5 $5 {This 
flashy move was first tried in correspondence play and recently introduced into 
high-level practice by Czech super-GM David Navara. I expect its popularity to grow 
in the upcoming years.} 8. dxe5 {Another move is 8. h3, used by GM Samuel Shankland 
to score a convincing victory against GM Awonder Liang and claim the US Championship 
in 2018. However, having investigated the move I have concluded that its main value 
lies in the surprise effect. I believe 8. de5 is more reliable in the long run, 
leading to a comfortable anti-IQP play.} Nh5 9. Be3 Nxe5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Nd2 Be6 12. 
Qa4 Qc7 {See also 12....Bd7} 13. Ngf3 Bd6 14. O-O O-O 15. Rfe1 Nf6 16. h3 $14 {White 
has reached a classical anti-IQP position with a small, but stable edge.} *

