1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 e5 8. dxe5 Nh5 
9. Be3 Nxe5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Qa4 Bd7 {Another logical posibility for 
Black.} 13. Ngf3 {White continues his development and is not afraid to part with his 
light squared-bishop.} a6 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Qc2 $14 {While the knight for bishop 
exchange has cost Black some time, it is doubtful whether it has really benefited 
him. In fact, White has strengthened his control over the d4 square and Black bishop 
pair is clearly not the most formidable one. White will continue with simple 
centralization, dictating the play.} *

