1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 g6 7. Nf3 Bf5 {The only 
way the move order with 5....g6 and 6....Nf6 can gain independent value. 7....Bg7 
would simply transpose to the 5....g6 lines.} 8. Bxf5 gxf5 9. Qb3 $1 {The simplest 
way to an edge, exploiting the fact that the white bishop already operates on the 
h2-b8 diagonal.} Qd7 {Note that 9....Qc8? would be met by 10. Be5!} 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. 
Bxe5 Bg7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Nf3 $14 {White has reached a stable positional and strategic 
advantage with minimum effort. Keep in mind a possible maneuver Ne1-d3, where the 
knight has access to 3 important squares: e5, c5 and f4.} *

