1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bf4 O-O 
9. Nbd2 Bf5 {In my view, a dubious concept. True, the light-squared bishops exchange 
is benefitial for Black. But he achieves it at a cost of weakening his pawn 
structure, which is neverthless a more important factor here.} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Ne5 
{From here on, the play acquires a very strategic character and many alternatives are 
available for both sides. It would be counterproductive to try and cover them all, so 
we will follow a game Sveshnikov-Shevelev 2017, which nicely demostrates White's 
assets and plans in further play.} e6 12. Qe2 Rc8 13. Nd3 Ne4 14. f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 
{The knight exchange favors White, as Black's king becomes more vulnerable without 
the knight on f6. White understands that and immediately follows with the right plan 
- g4!} Kh8 16. Kh1 Rg8 17. g4 fxg4 18. fxg4 Bf6 19. Qe2 $16 {White's kingside 
initiative guaranteed him a clear advantage in Sveshnikov-Shevelev 2017} *

