1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bf4 O-O 
9. Nbd2 Nh5 10. Be3 Qd6 {A more restrained approach compared to 10....f5. Note that 
10....Qc7 is simply a worse version of the game (the queen stands better on d6), 
without much independent value.} 11. Re1 Nf4 12. Bb5 {It is useful to put some 
pressure on the c6 knight and provoke the weaking ...a6 move.} Ne6 13. Nb3 $14 {We 
have reached a position which remains to be tested in practice. A complicated 
maneuvering game lies ahead, in which White holds a slight edge due to his better 
control of the center and more harmonious piece placement.} *

