1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6 {Planning to fianchetto his 
dark-squared bishop, Black decides on a different scheme of development than in the 
5...Qc7 and 5...Nf6 variations. I consider it to be a positionally-dubious way of 
playing, as now both Black will be significantly worse than their counterparts. As we 
will see, Black can try to compensate for this minus with dynamic play. But I believe 
that a precise reaction is enough for a definite edge for White.} 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O 
Nf6 {We will also deal with an original 7...Nh6 move.} 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Nbd2 Nh5 10. Be3 
f5 {This aggressive continuation happens to be the most popular one. However, if 
properly met, it creates more weakness than assets for Black.} 11. Nb3 f4 12. Bd2 Bg4 
{The only logical follow-up, intending ...e5.} 13. Be2 Qd6 14. Re1 $1 {It is 
important to restrain from the obvious 14. h3, as 14....Bxf3 15. Bxf3 e5 16. dxe5 
Nxe5 17. Bxh5 gxh5 18. Qxh5 Rf6! would give Black good compensation, while 17. Nd4 
would lead to a worse version of the game, without rooks being traded down the e 
file.} Rae8 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nd4 Nxf3+ 19. Nxf3 Rxe1+ 20. 
Bxe1 $16 {After the last precise move the situation has cleared. With Qb3/a4 coming 
next, White enjoys great play against Black's weak pawns.} *

