1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 e5 {This is the least popular of the 
four reasonable moves avilable for Black. The reason for this is clear: Black goes 
for an IQP position, which typically gives White a stable advantage.} 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. 
Qe2 Qe7 8. Be3 {I propose this relatively new move (played only once over the board), 
as I believe that the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is actually 
benefitial for White in this type of position. As you may have noticed, a similar 
idea occurs in one of the lines of the 5....Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 e5 variation.} 
Nxd3+ {Or 8....Nf6 9. Nf3 Nxd3+} 9. Qxd3 Nf6 10. Nf3 Qc7 11. O-O Be7 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. 
Rfe1 $14 {The basic factor of an assesment of the IQP positions is the control over 
d4/d5 square. Here White enjoys a total control over d4, which means that he will 
dictate the course of the game. Note that Black's bishop pair represents no real 
strenght, as both bishops are limited- the light-squared one by the black pawn on d5 
and the dark-squared one by White' dark-square control.} *

